<p>A Supperclub is a cross between a restaurant and a dinner party. It’s the ultimate example of a social dining experience, whereby people are united over a table not only to eat delicious home cooked food but also to enjoy the company of others.</p>

<p>As with most people, the way to retrace someone's love of food is through their mum. And so it happened with me. My mum, Maddy, not only grew up on a rural farm, eating only the produce of the land, but still spends most of her time creating mouth-watering meals for her ever-growing family.  </p>
<p>Living in the South of France, we had a constant stream of visitors staying with us throughout the year. My mum fed a core family of six three times a day, but the grub usually extended to a handful more mouths – family, friends and visitors – naturally turning our home into a supper club. My mum is my greatest source of inspiration for food and home-cooked meals, coupled with a deep love for story-telling.</p>
<p>This is a collection of my mum’s stories - told by her - growing up on a farm, living an organic and sustainable life; a collection of recipes and food adventures, which I feel privileged to have been brought up on.</p>
<p>I hope you enjoy them as much as I have.</p>
<p>Liv</p>

<span class="acc-trigger"><a href="#">How it all began</a></span>
<div class="acc-container">
	<div class="content">
		<p>My recipes have evolved and developed with the years.  They have adapted mainly to my children’s tastes although I have tried to impose my own sometimes.  Luckily we all agree about Brussels sprouts and cabbage and despise them utterly.  My inspiration has usually come from reading recipe books and the cooking pages of Good Housekeeping and other publications; sometimes a friend with something particularly toothsome and delicious is prepared to share her secret with me. My sister, Heather, and my Mother have also been generous with their recipes.</p>
		<p>I have always been a devotee of Margaret Costa who writes with such wisdom and elegance.  She says “When I am not rushed, I find cooking the most restful and soothing of all occupations, to beat and baste, to peel and chop and slice, to taste and test and stir and skim is “therapy”, what in the old days they used to call joy”. (Listening to Radio 4 goes very well with all these occupations, although liquidising tends to block out the sound.)</p>
		<p>Robert Carrier wrote a book entitled “Great Dishes of the World”. My copy is forty years old and has lost its cover and many of the pages are stained with the ingredients of that particular recipe.   The Osso Bucco page is covered in tomato sauce.  The illustrations look so very nineteen sixties; it makes me realise just how sophisticated and beautiful the modern cookery photos are. I also love Katie Stewart and John Tovey who both make you want to rush to the kitchen and start cooking.</p>
		<p>I have cooked in many kitchens of all shapes and sizes, ancient and modern. Size really does not matter, a decent work surface does; in fact I find that cooking in my little kitchen is very practical and I can do everything without having to move very far. The rest is just a question of wanting to create something that makes you and your friends and family happy. A little praise for the cook will go a long way to getting your next invitation. My family and friends have all eaten their way through successes and failures and given me their invaluable comments and opinions and helped me to know which dishes they like best.</p>
		<p>My very grateful thanks to my familly and friends for your skill, generosity,  expertise,  excellent judgement and good taste in making the word flesh, so to speak. Without you there would have been no “Notes from a supper club”.</p>
		<p>So thank-you to all of you for your encouragement and enthusiasm. I have so much enjoyed the happy times cooking for you and there was a dose of love in every dish.</p>
