<span class="acc-trigger"><a href="#">TOMATO MEMORIES</a></span>
<div class="acc-container">
	<div class="content">
		<p>We had the most enormous greenhouse where I grew up at Church Farm in Lancashire. My mother spent most of her time there; it was her refuge, laboratory and favourite place to be. I remember her asking me once at what moment could I say “Now, doing this, being here, means total happiness to me”. I have often thought about that; in any case, her answer was being in the greenhouse, looking after her tomatoes, nursing her seedlings and listening to her little transistor radio. That radio was a real miracle as it survived more than one ducking in a bucket of water.  The smell of fresh tomatoes still growing on the vine always takes me back to our greenhouse and the heady, tropical jungle it became in the summer.  The only thing was, how to use so many tomatoes? Here is one idea.</p>
		<ul class="circle_list">
			<li><strong>Tomato Tart</strong></li>
			<li>My friend Nina’s recipe:  My son Hugo and I went to stay with Nina and Vasco in Madrid ten years ago. We had a wonderful weekend and Nina made this delicious tart. Thelma the dog was an integral part of life and probably got in the way by lying on the kitchen floor.  Nina now has a new dog which is not called Louise.</li>
		</ul>
		<p>Line a quiche tin with puff pastry (or basic shortcrust) I read that even Saint Delia now buys the ready-made stuff and so do I.</p>
		<p>Spread some mustard over the pastry and then some chopped-up bacon which you do not need to fry beforehand. Now a layer of some kind of tasty, melty cheese.  Nina used Comté, but honestly, Cheddar or Lancashire would be just as good. In fact, support your home industry and buy British if that is where you happen to be. <p> 
		<p>Now, slice up lots of good, ripe tomatoes and put them in circles, at least two layers deep:  drizzle some olive oil over, and salt and black pepper, maybe a few fresh basil leaves if you have some to hand. I think this needs an hour in a moderately- hot oven, say 180C and then left to cool a bit.  Much nicer eaten lukewarm.<p>
		<p>I remember putting just such a tart in the oven and then going off to the airport with my daughter Olivia to pick up one of her friends. The tart went on cooking for two hours until we returned but seemed only the better for my forgetfulness.<p>
	</div>
</div>

<span class="acc-trigger"><a href="#">Red Pepper and Goat’s cheese tart</a></span>
<div class="acc-container">
	<div class="content">
		<p>I have had so much success with this recipe which can be prepared for the oven in five minutes. </p>
		<ul class="circle_list">
			<li>You will need some bought puff pastry.  I would never even attempt to make puff pastry; life really is too short..</li>
			<li>Some grilled and skinned red peppers; this is a bit smelly and the whole house will reek for hours so if you want to go for the ones in jars I would do so.
		    If it is summer and the barbecue is nice and hot this is the perfect opportunity to throw a few peppers on, blacken them nicely, roll them up in newspaper, let them cool and then rub the skins off.  This is what my daughter Liv and she then stores it in batches in oil.</li>
			<li>Some goat’s cheese, the log sort is cheaper than the “crottins” and perfect.</li>
			<li>Bacon bits</li>
		</ul>
		<p>Cut the pastry into oblongs (about 4x6 inches). Put the bacon bits on the pastry and place slices of the goat’s cheese over them.  Now arrange the pieces of red pepper over the top. Turn up the edges of the pastry to make little box shapes. Brush the pastry with beaten egg and bake in the oven at 200 C for 20 minutes.</p>
		<p>You can serve this alone or perhaps on a bed of a few rocket leaves and a drizzle of olive oil.</p>
