<span class="acc-trigger"><a href="#">Quiches</a></span>
<div class="acc-container">
	<div class="content">
		<p>Quiches have to be the most versatile of dishes; as satisfying and easy to make as they are delicious to eat. They can adapt to so many different occasions and the variations on the basic theme are endless. </p>
		<p>They can be lunch with a simple salad, the first course of a dinner or a brilliant item for the picnic hamper. If rain spoils the outdoor feast you can eat the quiche at home and that is more cheerful and less of an anticlimax than sandwiches.</p>
		<p>Yes, you may buy the pastry; it usually is shortcrust but actually puff pastry is excellent.  In France, we have the choice between ready-rolled rectangular or round. I do hope UK supermarkets have got around to the fact that ready-rolled circular shaped pastry is so much more useful than the rectangular.  Liv, thanks for trying to educate them!! I wonder if they’ll listen to your advice.</p>
		<p>Quiches do look charming cooked in a white ceramic dish with fluted edges; however, the quiche does not cook as well as in the plain old metal type and often the pastry has a soggy bottom. </p>
		<p>Line your tin with the pastry and then scatter fried bacon bits over it; if rashers are the only choice just cut them up with scissors. My son Hugo tells me it is difficult to find “les lardons” in England; different attitude to bacon I suppose.</p>
		<p>Now add a layer of grated Gruyère and some rounds of goat’s cheese or blue cheese if you fancy.  Mix up 5 eggs with a big tub of cream which can be crème fraiche or single or double cream: Keep away from milk. Season well with salt and freshly ground pepper and pour over the rest. </p>
		<p>Cook at 180C for about 40 minutes by which time the quiche should be all puffed up and golden with a firm filling. I actually think this is better served warm rather than piping hot.</p>
		<p>A true “Quiche Lorraine” has no cheese.  How boring of it.</p>
		<p>Variations on a theme could be lots of fried leeks and bacon, or fried mushrooms, or smoked salmon, or onions which have been cooked a long age gently in butter until caramelised.</p>
		<p>Invent your own as long as you stick to the basic principle.</p>  
	</div>
