	<div class="content">
        <p><strong>Five Easy pieces.</strong></p>
		<p>Five Salads that can be thrown together very easily and served with panache.</p>
		<p><strong>Orange, Prawn and Smoked Salmon.</strong></p>
		<p>I first ate this in a little restaurant in Milan and it was so refreshing and unusual that I had to add it to my repertoire.</p>
		<p>The recipe really is in the title. Choose whatever interesting salad leaves you like. Peel and slice some nice juicy oranges and add some cooked prawns and some smoked salmon cubes. </p>
		<p>Mix them with the salad leaves and coat in a tasty vinaigrette; snip some chives or perhaps some pretty, feathery dill over the top.</p>
		<p><strong>Warm Scallop salad.</strong></p>
		<p>Wash the scallops and fry them gently in some butter for about five minutes and add a little lemon juice.</p>
		<p>Add to your salad leaves with salt, black pepper and olive oil and toss.</p> 
		<p>You could add any other warm fish for another flavour and texture.</p>
		<p><strong>Green Bean and Foie Gras salad.</strong></p>
		<p>Cook the beans; I usually buy them frozen and they are excellent.</p>
		<p>Chop up some foie gras which can be duck (cheaper and just as good).</p>
		<p>Add to the warm beans and toss in olive oil and balsamic vinegar, salt and pepper to taste.</p>
		<p><strong>Salad of Green Beans and Butter Beans.</strong></p>
		<p>Cook the green beans as before. Open a tin of butter beans or any other type of white beans. Drain them and add to the green beans.</p>
		<p>Add lemon juice, olive oil, salt and black pepper. Toss the salad and sprinkle some freshly chopped parsley on top.</p>
		<p><strong>Blue Cheese and Walnut Salad.</strong></p>
		<p>Fry some walnuts gently in butter until they are nice and toasty. Fry some bacon bits.</p>
		<p>Chop up some blue cheese, the variety is your choice, French, Italian or English. Take a packet of baby spinach and add all the ingredients to the leaves.</p>
		<p>Toss in olive oil and balsamic vinegar, add salt and pepper.</p>
		<p><strong>Ok, maybe 6 salad recipes….</strong></p>
		<p><strong>Waldorf Salad.</strong></p>
		<p>I did say five easy pieces but I thought you should also have a recipe for Waldorf Salad just in case you happen to have a few waldorfs lying around doing nothing.</p>
		<p>This is Robert Carrier’s version but I think there really is only one.</p>
		<ul class="circle_list">
        	<li>6 eating apples</li>
			<li>Juice of 2 lemons</li>
			<li>6 stalks of celery</li>
			<li>50 gr walnuts</li>
			<li>Salad leaves</li>
			<li>Maoyonaise</li>
        </ul>
		<p>Core and dice the apples and sprinkle with lemon juice. Add the sliced celery and walnuts (toasted or not). Toss together with the mayonnaise and pile into a bowl lined with salad leaves.</p>
		<p>You can also add some diced, cooked chicken and maybe scatter a few finely-chopped celery leaves on top. It always seems such a shame to throw them away.</p>
		<p><strong>And just one more….</strong></p>
		<p><strong>Hot Goat's cheese salad.</strong></p>
		<p>This is utterly delicious and so simple.</p>
		<p>Take some “crottins” and allow two for each person.  Now wrap each one round with a slice of prosciutto and lay on a baking tray. Drizzle a little olive oil over them.</p>
		<p>Cook in a moderate oven for about ten minutes or until you see the cheeses are getting well cooked without actually falling to pieces: the slice of ham will encourage them to keep their shape.</p>
		<p>Serve on a bed of roquette or whatever salad leaves you fancy. Scatter a few fried pine nuts over and a little more olive oil.</p>   
